VARIANT CREUTZFELDT-JAKOB DISEASE, FIFTH DEATH - SPAIN (CANTABRIA)
******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Fri 6 Mar 2009
Source: Associated Press report [edited]
<http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gAFZ583FrJLfABJMsHuJ1PhcU-cw>


Spain reports 5th human death from mad cow disease
--------------------------------------------------
The Spanish government late Friday [6 Mar 2009] confirmed the
country's 5th fatality from the human variant of mad cow disease, a
woman who died in the northern city of Santander in January [2009].

The health ministry said laboratory tests confirmed that the woman
had [variant] Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD) as the human variant of
bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), or mad cow disease, is known.
"The appearance of sporadic cases of the disease does not indicate
new risks for the health of the public," it said in a statement.

The last death in Spain which was confirmed to have been due to the
brain-wasting disease took place in August 2008 in the northwestern
region of Castilla and Leon. Spain recorded its 1st human death from
mad cow disease in June 2005 when a 26-year-old woman succumbed to it
in Madrid.

More than 200 people around the world are suspected to have died,
most of them in Britain, from the human variant of the disease, which
was 1st described in 1996. Scientists believe the disease was caused
by using infected parts of cattle to make feed for other cattle.
Authorities believe eating meat from infected animals can trigger the
human variant of the fatal brain-wasting disease. The 27-member EU,
of which Spain is part, has banned high-risk materials such as spinal
cord from use in feed, and stricter labelling was also introduced.

[Byline: Al Goodman]

